00:21:21.130 --> 00:21:22.960
This is just them across age.

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:24.830
So on the bottom of the screen,

00:21:24.830 --> 00:21:28.050
you'll see age here from 11 to 15

00:21:28.050 --> 00:21:30.620
and you'll see if the
young people in your life

00:21:30.620 --> 00:21:32.330
are around 11 years old,

00:21:32.330 --> 00:21:35.812
about 48% of their peers
own a mobile device.

00:21:35.812 --> 00:21:39.449
As we get older in our sample,

00:21:39.449 --> 00:21:42.284
we get up here to almost full saturation.

00:21:42.284 --> 00:21:45.840
This line up here is access
to the internet at home.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:48.440
So something we used to worry
a lot about in education

00:21:48.440 --> 00:21:49.810
was a digital divide.

00:21:49.810 --> 00:21:52.370
So some kids not having
access to the internet,

00:21:52.370 --> 00:21:53.875
that's no longer true.

00:21:53.875 --> 00:21:57.340
And smartphone use is actually higher

00:21:57.340 --> 00:21:59.486
among children from lower income families.

00:21:59.486 --> 00:22:02.997
So we don't see that
traditional digital divide.

00:22:02.997 --> 00:22:06.620
We see few differences in
mobile device ownership

00:22:06.620 --> 00:22:07.870
by socioeconomic status

00:22:07.870 --> 00:22:09.260
but as I'm gonna show you,

00:22:09.260 --> 00:22:12.502
we see differences in
experiences and maybe effects.

00:22:12.502 --> 00:22:14.342
So what does this all mean?

00:22:14.342 --> 00:22:16.646
If you pick up a paper,

00:22:16.646 --> 00:22:18.320
probably today or tomorrow,

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:21.313
you'll read some story
about how digital devices

00:22:21.313 --> 00:22:23.102
are ruining our children,

00:22:23.102 --> 00:22:25.469
smartphones are destroying a generation.

00:22:25.469 --> 00:22:28.180
Recently we had a number of psychologists

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:30.384
sign a letter, an open letter to Apple,

00:22:30.384 --> 00:22:32.570
demanding that tech companies

00:22:32.570 --> 00:22:35.140
end their addictive
practices toward our children

00:22:35.140 --> 00:22:37.282
based on evidence, they said,

00:22:37.282 --> 00:22:40.270
that smartphones were
making our children lonely,

00:22:40.270 --> 00:22:43.170
depressed, suicidal,

00:22:43.170 --> 00:22:44.840
stealing things from them.

00:22:44.840 --> 00:22:46.008
These are big claims,

00:22:46.008 --> 00:22:47.680
these are big claims.

00:22:47.680 --> 00:22:49.090
So is this constant connection,

00:22:49.090 --> 00:22:50.330
is it harmful to our kids?

00:22:50.330 --> 00:22:52.365
And I'm gonna show you
two pieces of evidence.

00:22:52.365 --> 00:22:54.950
The first one is from a team in Britain

00:22:54.950 --> 00:22:57.260
and they've assembled
large amasses of data

00:22:57.260 --> 00:22:59.016
on hundreds of thousands of adolescents.

00:22:59.016 --> 00:23:00.260
Now these are surveys,

00:23:00.260 --> 00:23:01.624
so just correlational research

00:23:01.624 --> 00:23:04.710
asking kids to report
on the amount of time

00:23:04.710 --> 00:23:08.294
they're on their devices and
their mental health problems.

00:23:08.294 --> 00:23:10.070
I'm gonna show you a graph here

00:23:10.070 --> 00:23:11.151
but the thing to focus on

00:23:11.151 --> 00:23:15.340
is just this pattern, a
Goldilocks effect, right?

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:17.660
So here are the kids that
are not on screen time

00:23:17.660 --> 00:23:19.410
at all in a day.

00:23:19.410 --> 00:23:21.620
Here are the kids in
those one or two hours

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:23.925
and then here's kind of a
deterioration of wellbeing

00:23:23.925 --> 00:23:25.493
across time.

00:23:25.493 --> 00:23:27.910
So described as a Goldilocks effect,

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:29.277
the kids that are on not at all,

00:23:29.277 --> 00:23:31.150
don't look so great on mental health,

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:34.600
the kids in the one to
two hour range look good

00:23:34.600 --> 00:23:36.320
and then out at the lower ends of the tail

00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:37.370
or the higher ends of the tail,

00:23:37.370 --> 00:23:39.390
those kids are experiencing some problems.

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:41.884
Now remember, this is correlational.

00:23:41.884 --> 00:23:43.380
The other thing to remember

00:23:43.380 --> 00:23:45.906
is that these data

00:23:45.906 --> 00:23:47.990
and all the data that are presented,

00:23:47.990 --> 00:23:49.476
including the data where people

00:23:49.476 --> 00:23:52.717
argue that smartphones are
causing mental health problems,

00:23:52.717 --> 00:23:56.063
these actually explain
less than one percent

00:23:56.063 --> 00:23:59.660
of the differences between
kids and their mental health.

00:23:59.660 --> 00:24:00.788
So said another way,

00:24:00.788 --> 00:24:05.788
99.5% of the reasons that kids
are different than each other

00:24:06.170 --> 00:24:07.280
